\begin_layout Standard
Among the most important consequences of his work was the idea that consumers could not be maximising intertemporal utility,
 using interest rates to discount future costs and benefits.
 Indeed,
 as will be seen in later chapters,
 there is a wealth of empirical evidence suggesting that individuals do not,
 and cannot apply consistent discount factors to the future and take decisions maximising intertemporal utility.
 In practice this means that the choice of what goods and services to consume,
 and how much to consume and to save,
 will be dominated by a few rules which produce satisfactory (but not optimal) outcomes.
 Simon referred to such decision rules as 
\emph on
