\emph default
 rationality of orthodox economics.
 It will be seen that the way individuals develop such rules means that their decisions may be very different those that would have resulted from intertemporal utility maximisation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cyert and March,
 Richardson and others applied these insights to the theory of the firm,
 and again demonstrated that firms cannot simply maximise profits because the information and knowledge required simply do not exist.
 The firms have to use policies and procedures which produce satisfactory results.
 It is impossible to know whether these would have been optimal.
 This applies particularly when developing new products or opening new markets.
 Demand curves and marginal costs are unknown in such cases,
 and will change with as the product enters a new market.
 New investment is inevitably a question of taking a decision under extreme uncertainty and with very little reliable knowledge.
 As 
